You’re thinking about replay protection and tenant isolation. Merge webhook handler validates a timestamp window and resolves org from the linked account in your DB, not from the payload.

Queueing and retry behavior is thoughtful. You centralize job retry options, support explicit job IDs, do enqueue retry with jitter and metrics, and you use BullMQ’s UnrecoverableError for non-retryable fetch failures.

Permissions middleware is more than “role check”. You’ve got role bypass for OWNER/ADMIN plus org settings and per-user permission grants, and you’re enforcing “owner or explicit permission” patterns for landing pages.

The biggest “is this decent” issues to fix

These are the ones that can bite you even if everything “works” in happy-path testing.

1) Webhook raw body middleware ordering (high risk)

In app.ts, you register express.json() globally, then later register the Merge/Gong/Grain webhook routes with express.raw(). In Express, middleware order matters, the JSON parser will typically consume the request body before the later express.raw() gets a chance. That can break signature verification or force you into lossy reconstruction.

Fix: move all app.post("/api/webhooks/*", express.raw(...)) routes before app.use(express.json(...)), or use the verify option on express.json() to capture the raw body for those routes.

2) Webhook idempotency is in-memory only (high risk in production scaling)

markWebhookEventIfNew uses an in-process Map with a 5 minute TTL. That prevents duplicates only inside a single Node process. If you ever run 2 instances (or a restart happens), you can double-process deliveries.

Fix: put the dedupe key in Redis (SET NX with EX), or persist in Postgres with a unique constraint on (orgId, eventType, dataId).

3) Rate limiter IP correctness behind proxies (common gotcha)

Your rate limiter keys off req.ip. If you deploy behind a proxy or load balancer and don’t set app.set("trust proxy", ...), you can end up rate limiting the proxy IP, not the user IP. I didn’t see trust proxy configured.

Fix: set trust proxy appropriately for Fly, Render, etc, and consider using a stable header like x-forwarded-for only when trusted.

4) PII masking is a good start, but expect false positives and misses

The PII masker is deterministic and runs before sending text to the model, that’s the right privacy stance.
But the credit card regex is “16 digits shaped”, there’s no Luhn validation, so you’ll redact lots of non-card numbers.

Fix: add a Luhn check and tighten patterns, then expand tests around real transcript edge cases.

5) Webhook dedupe key choice might still collide

You build dedupe keys from eventType and a dataId derived from data.id, data.remote_id, or linked_account.id. That’s reasonable, but it’s not guaranteed unique across all event types and payload shapes forever.

Fix: if Merge provides a unique delivery ID, prefer that. Otherwise include timestamp plus a hash of raw body, or include more payload identity fields.

Bottom line

If “decent work” means “would a senior engineer look at this and say it’s real software”, yes. The structure, security intent, tests around signature verification, and the queue/retry setup are all strong signals.

If “decent work” means “safe to run for paying customers without nasty surprises”, you’re close, but you should fix the webhook middleware ordering and distributed idempotency first. Those two are the kind of bugs that create silent data corruption or double-processing.

