Yep, a few more code-level things worth calling out, beyond “docs are stale”.

High leverage fixes
1) CSRF middleware can throw on bad token length

crypto.timingSafeEqual(a, b) throws if buffers are different lengths. Your CSRF check does not guard for that, so a malformed x-csrf-token can turn into a 500 instead of a clean 403.

Fix: check csrfToken.length === expectedCsrf.length before calling timingSafeEqual, or wrap the compare in a try/catch and treat errors as “invalid CSRF”.

2) Request logging can leak sensitive query params

You log req.originalUrl for every request. If you ever put tokens, magic links, share links, or IDs in query strings, they’ll end up in logs.

Fix: log req.path (no query string), or scrub known sensitive params before logging.

3) CSRF design is unusual, and only helps in a cookie-based threat model

Your CSRF token is an HMAC of the session token, and the client must send it via x-csrf-token for write requests.
If your session token is stored in JS (common with Authorization or x-session-token), then CSRF is mostly irrelevant, and XSS is the real concern. Not “wrong”, just make sure you’re not relying on CSRF as your main protection.

Medium priority
4) API key compare is fine, but token parsing is a bit permissive

API keys are stored hashed and looked up by hash, that’s good.
Minor: Authorization: Bearer <key> extraction doesn’t trim, so odd whitespace could cause confusing failures.

5) IP based controls depend on trust proxy

Your security policy boundary enforces IP allowlists using req.ip (with a comment saying it honors trust proxy “when configured”).
If you deploy behind a proxy and don’t set trust proxy, this can be inaccurate and break allowlists or rate limits.

Low priority polish
6) Session lastSeen updates are fire-and-forget, which is fine, but watch DB load

Session middleware updates lastSeenAt on every request.
At scale this becomes write-heavy. A simple improvement is to only update if lastSeenAt is older than N minutes.

If you want a brutally practical “what do I fix first” list: fix distributed webhook idempotency, then the CSRF length crash, then log scrubbing, then trust proxy. Those are the ones that turn into production incidents.

