Security and privacy

Sentry and logs could capture sensitive payloads. You have good observability hooks, but make sure request bodies, webhook payloads, and transcript text are never attached to errors or breadcrumbs. A single unredacted transcript in an error event is a bad day.

CORS allowlist is good, but watch new environments. When you add preview URLs, staging, or a custom domain feature, people often “temporarily” widen CORS and forget to tighten it back up.

Password protected pages. If you’re doing “password protected landing pages”, confirm the implementation is hashing passwords (bcrypt/argon2), has rate limiting on the password check, and never leaks “page exists” details differently for wrong vs missing password.

Multi tenancy and authorization correctness

Enforce org scoping at the DB query level, not only middleware. Middleware checks are great, but the most dangerous bug is a single Prisma query missing orgId filtering in a route handler or worker.

Workers need the same auth boundaries as API routes. Anything pulling a job off the queue should fetch the org context and only touch data for that org. A job payload that only contains an ID can become a cross-tenant issue if IDs are guessable or mishandled.

Reliability and data integrity

External API calls need hard timeouts plus circuit breaker fallbacks. You already have resilience patterns in places, but make sure all outbound calls have timeouts and bounded retries. “Retry forever” is how you rack up Stripe, OpenAI, or Merge bills.

Transactional boundaries around “create record then enqueue jobs”. If you do “write DB record then enqueue a job”, make sure you can recover if enqueue fails, or if the job runs before the transaction is committed. The clean pattern is outbox table or “enqueue after commit”.

Queue concurrency and backpressure. If embeddings and summarization are heavy, you want explicit concurrency limits per queue, plus per-org throttles, otherwise one tenant can starve everyone.

Maintainability

“God files” and cross-cutting middleware. You have several modules that do a lot. It works, but it raises the cost of safe changes. Splitting billing, webhooks, and security policy into smaller units will pay off fast if you keep iterating.

Stale features toggles. You have multiple env flags and conditional behaviors. Over time, unused flags become “unknown unknowns” and cause weird prod-only bugs. It’s worth pruning.

